","1214":"1214","1148":"1148","1135":"1135","1200":"1200","1145":"1145","1199":"1199","Egypt":"Egypt","nameMeanings":[{"name":"d'Encre","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Erwin, Herta.","English (Kent): variant of <b>Dench</b>, an ethnic name for someone from Denmark, from Middle English <i>denshe</i>, <i>dench</i> ‘Danish’ (Old English <i>denisc</i>). There were many Danes in England in the Middle Ages, not only the long-established settlers in the Danelaw region, but also more recent immigrants."],"variants":[{"name":"Denmark","meanings":["English (Norfolk): ethnic name denoting someone from Denmark (see   Dence  ). In the British Isles this name is found mainly in East Anglia.","Americanized form of German <b>Dennemark</b>, ethnic name for someone from Denmark, from Middle Low German <i>Dennemarken</i>."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Clermont","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Jacques, Georges, Normand, Pierre, Armand, Edouard, Gaston, Ghislaine, Gilles, Henri, Herve, Jean Francois.","French and English (Middlesex, of Norman and French Huguenot origin): habitational name from any o